result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th or 6th) and Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Joseph Thomas Long was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th), a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
9:35 AM Defendant Joseph Thomas Long in court, in custody.  Attorney Michael Charles Hoffman in court for Joseph Thomas Long.  Attorney Chad C La Lor in court for State of Wisconsin. State has joint recommendation as follows: 6 years prison fashioned as 3 years initial confinement, 3 years Extended Supervision, Consecutive to Barron County Case number 20CF347, $2000 fine plus costs and surcharges, Lifetime Revocation, 36 months IID, AODA Assessment and Safety plan, 73 days credit. State will dismiss Counts 2 & 3 and all trailing citations. 
Atty Hoffman asserts he is in agreement.
Defendant pleads Guilty. 
Atty Hoffman does stipulate to a factual basis. 
Defendant pleads guilty to charge. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.  The Defendant understands all the rights he is waiving by his plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered. Any remaining charges are dismissed. 
Court Orders: 
Count 1 - 6 years prison fashioned as 3 years initial confinement, 3 years Extended Supervision, Consecutive to Barron County Case number 20CF347, $2000 fine plus costs and surcharges, Lifetime Revocation, 36 months IID, AODA Assessment and Safety plan, 73 days credit. Court indicates Defendant is eligible for Substance Abuse Program but not the Challenge. All other remaining Counts are dismissed along with all trailing citations.

Defendant has not applied for any counsel. Court questions defendant as to why he hasn't applied for Counsel. Defendant indicates he doesn't have access to a phone in the jail. Court questions jailers. Jailers indicate that defendant does have access to a phone to reach out to counsel. Defendant is ready to proceed to Preliminary hearing. Court questions defendant on waiver of time limits. Defendant asserts he would like to move forward for Preliminary hearing.

01:30 PM Defendant Joseph Thomas Long in court with attorney Michael Charles Hoffman.  Defendant Joseph Thomas Long in custody.  Chad C La Lor appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant's address updated and amended on complaint.  Attorney/defendant acknowledges receipt of criminal complaint, waives reading. Court will set matter for Preliminary Hearing. There are two trailing citations 22TR268 and 22TR269. Atty Hoffman pleads not guilty on behalf of defendant
Court requests $3500 cash bond with conditions of   No operation of a motor vehicle unless Defendant has valid permit or license.  No use or possession of alcohol ad no frequenting establishments whose primary is alcohol. State goes through prior criminal history of defendant. Pending felony counts in Barron County including failures to appear. Defendant does have OWI's and PAC's in Barron County. State indicates that the failure to appears and Cumberland address are some of the reasons for the request of cash. 
Atty Hoffman questions defendant. Defendant has resided in Cumberland all of his life. Defendant was working when he was arrested. Defendant has no money to post. Defendant is not on any holds that he knows of. 
Court has several concerns. Court orders $3500 cash bond with conditions of No operation of a motor vehicle unless Defendant has valid permit or license.  No use or possession of alcohol and no frequenting establishments whose primary purpose is alcohol. Court offers text message reminder slip.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for February 2, 2022 at 09:45 am.  Status conference scheduled for February 1, 2022 at 01:30 pm.
